<subSubSection id="C32CDFE1BC7FD921FF35FF4B14B0FE60" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B898C6ABC7FD921FF35FF4B14B0FE60" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1869]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FF35FF4B1701FF7C" bold="true" box="[151,273,151,176]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Readily recognized by the following characters: Body rounded or ovoid, tumid, 
<quantity id="4CCE218FBC7FD921FB1AFF4B1352FF63" box="[1208,1346,151,176]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.85" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="2.2" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" unit="mm" value="2.85" valueMax="3.5" valueMin="2.2">2.2–3.5 mm</quantity>
in total length, with densely distributed, lanceolate silvery or silky, scale-like setae which are very easily rubbed off (during collecting and/or mounting); head short and broadened, wider than high in frontal view; dorsal body surface weakly shining, usually with dark, simple setae, in addition to scalelike setae; eye small; antenna generally slender and long; bases of mesepisternum and metapleuron often roundly infuscate; hemelytron strongly declivous at cuneal fracture; left paramere thickened; and endosoma usually elongate, C- or J-shaped, often with median appendages. Detailed diagnoses and taxonomic characters are provided by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA7F19BBC7FD921FC7FFEB31264FE44" author="Schuh" box="[989,1140,367,392]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Schuh, R. T. (1984) Revision of the Phylinae (Hemiptera, Miridae) of the Indo-Pacific. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 177, 1 - 476." type="journal article" year="1984">
Schuh (
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FB90FEAC127CFE44" box="[1074,1132,368,392]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="1984.0">1984</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
as 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FB3BFEAC136FFE44" authority="Odhiambo" authorityName="Odhiambo" box="[1177,1407,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Ambonea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FB3BFEAC1313FE44" box="[1177,1283,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Ambonea</emphasis>
Odhiambo
</taxonomicName>
(a junior synonym) and 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA7F19BBC7FD921FE25FE48148CFE60" author="Schuh" box="[391,668,404,429]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Schuh, R. T. &amp; Menard, K. (2011) Santalalean-feeding plant bugs: ten new species in the genus Hypseloecus Reuter from Australia and South Africa (Heteroptera: Miridae: Phylinae): their hosts and placement in the Pilophorini. Australian Journal of Entomology, 50, 365 - 392. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1440 - 6055.2011.00829. x" type="journal article" year="2011">
Schuh &amp; Menard (
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FDF5FE481483FE60" box="[599,659,404,428]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2011.0">2011</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32CDFE1BC7FD921FF65FE6B1768FA98" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B898C6ABC7FD921FF65FE6B1410FD3C" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1869]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FF65FE6B175CFE1C" bold="true" box="[199,332,439,464]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Discussion.</emphasis>
This unique pilophorine genus is easily recognized by the above-mentioned characters. The significantly ovoid, thick body shape is unusual within the tribe 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FCD0FE0015E3FE39" box="[882,1011,476,501]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Pilophorini">Pilophorini</taxonomicName>
, in which predominantly ant-mimetic members are accommodated (Schuh, 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FDE8FDDC1495FDD4" box="[586,645,512,536]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="1989.0">1989</number>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA7F19BBC7FD921FD37FDDC1582FDD4" author="Yasunaga" box="[661,914,511,536]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Yasunaga, T., Yamada, K. &amp; Artchawakom, T. (2014) Additional records and descriptions of the ant-mimetic plant bug genus Pilophorus from Thailand (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Miridae: Phylinae: Pilophorini). Zootaxa, 3795 (1), 1 - 15. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3795.1.1" type="journal article" year="2014">
Yasunaga et al., 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FCF5FDDC1582FDD4" box="[855,914,512,536]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2014.0">2014</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA7F19BBC7FD921FC03FDDC12DCFDD4" author="Yasunaga" box="[929,1228,511,536]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Yasunaga, T. &amp; Schuh, R. T. (2013) Morphologically novel members of the ant-mimetic plant bug genus Pilophorus Hahn found in Thailand, with descriptions of three new species (Heteroptera: Miridae: Phylinae: Pilophorini). American Museum Novitates, 3768, 1 - 18. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1206 / 3768.2" type="journal article" year="2013">
Yasunaga &amp; Schuh, 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FB2DFDDC12DCFDD4" box="[1167,1228,512,536]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2013.0">2013</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Such a far from antlike body shape of 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FE01FDF81420FDF0" box="[419,560,548,572]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FE01FDF81420FDF0" box="[419,560,548,572]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Hypseloecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species may have certain advantages as an adaptation to the unique host preference. Their appearance densely covered with silvery, scale-like setae (which are very easily rubbed off while being collected as in 
<figureCitation id="130D90EFBC7FD921FE3BFDB017F0FD48" box="[409,480,620,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1628,1650]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,193,1606]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1437,193,1607]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Habitus images of living adult individuals of Hypseloecus species. A. H. siamensis holotype female on Scurrula sp. 1. B. H. castaneus female (SERS). C. H. castaneus male (missing scalelike setae, Nakhon Nayok). D. H. katrinae male (Nakhon Nayok). E. H. nigrobrevis holotype female (SERS)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/290611/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
Fig. 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FE70FDB017F0FD48" box="[466,480,620,644]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
B 
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FE5DFDB1140EFD48" box="[511,542,621,644]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">vs.</emphasis>
C and 
<figureCitation id="130D90EFBC7FD921FDDCFDB014D4FD48" box="[638,708,620,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1937,1959]" captionTargetBox="[165,1423,447,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[165,1424,447,1916]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. Habitus images of living adult individuals of Hypseloecus species. A. H. phuvasae holotype female (SERS). B. H. sakaerat holotype male (SERS). C. H. schuhianus male (SERS). D. H. schuhianus female (missing scalelike setae, SERS) (Nakhon Nayok)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/290615/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
Fig. 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FD15FDB014D4FD48" box="[695,708,620,644]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
C 
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FD46FDB11513FD48" box="[740,771,621,644]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">vs.</emphasis>
D) on the body surface makes them rather cryptic and harmonious with the habitat, or surfaces of their host plants (
<figureCitation id="130D90EFBC7FD921FCE9FD53159FFD64" box="[843,911,655,680]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1628,1650]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,193,1606]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1437,193,1607]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Habitus images of living adult individuals of Hypseloecus species. A. H. siamensis holotype female on Scurrula sp. 1. B. H. castaneus female (SERS). C. H. castaneus male (missing scalelike setae, Nakhon Nayok). D. H. katrinae male (Nakhon Nayok). E. H. nigrobrevis holotype female (SERS)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/290611/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
Fig. 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FC22FD4C159FFD64" box="[896,911,656,680]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A). Incidentally, 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FBECFD4C12CBFD64" box="[1102,1243,656,680]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FBECFD4C12CBFD64" box="[1102,1243,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Hypseloecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
members at first sight resemble 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FEE5FD6817C5FD00" box="[327,469,692,716]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Coridromius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FEE5FD6817C5FD00" box="[327,469,692,716]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Coridromius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species of the subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FCA1FD681584FD01" box="[771,916,692,717]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Orthotylinae">Orthotylinae</taxonomicName>
; the latter always has very tumid, developed metafemora, however (
<figureCitation id="130D90EFBC7FD921FE38FD0B17CDFD3C" box="[410,477,727,752]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1843,1865]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,193,1820]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1437,193,1821]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 9. Habitus images of living adult individuals of Hypseloecus species and other related or similar appearing Miridae. A. H. sericosagus holotype male (Nakhon Nayok). B. H. sericosagus female (SERS). C. Coridromius testaceous of the subfamily Orthotylinae (SERS), a sample image for comparison. D. Male of a pilophorine, Aloea nairobi Schuh (at Nairobi National Museum, Kenya), associated only with Aloe monocots in the Ethiopian Region. E. Same, female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/290616/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
Fig. 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FE6CFD0417CDFD3C" box="[462,477,728,752]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
C).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B898C6ABC7FD921FF65FD201758FBDC" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1869]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
<bibRefCitation id="EFA7F19BBC7FD921FF65FD2017C8FCD8" author="Schuh" box="[199,472,764,789]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Schuh, R. T. &amp; Menard, K. (2011) Santalalean-feeding plant bugs: ten new species in the genus Hypseloecus Reuter from Australia and South Africa (Heteroptera: Miridae: Phylinae): their hosts and placement in the Pilophorini. Australian Journal of Entomology, 50, 365 - 392. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1440 - 6055.2011.00829. x" type="journal article" year="2011">
Schuh &amp; Menard (
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FE34FD2017C0FCD8" box="[406,464,764,788]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2011.0">2011</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
for the first time documented that 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FCFFFD2015FAFCD8" box="[861,1002,764,788]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FCFFFD2015FAFCD8" box="[861,1002,764,788]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Hypseloecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are associated strictly with the hemiparasitic Santalalean host plants, although a single European species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FC56FCFD12BAFCF4" authority="Puton" authorityName="Puton" box="[1012,1194,800,824]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Sthenarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="visci">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FC56FCFD125CFCFB" box="[1012,1100,800,824]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">H. visci</emphasis>
(Puton)
</taxonomicName>
is known to feed on 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FF35FC991726FC90" box="[151,310,836,860]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Santalaceae" genus="Viscum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Santalales" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="album">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FF35FC991726FC90" box="[151,310,836,860]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Viscum album</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. (
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FEC4FC9817FEFC91" box="[358,494,836,861]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Santalaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Santalales" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Santalaceae</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA7F19BBC7FD921FDA4FC981488FC91" author="Schuh" box="[518,664,836,861]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Schuh, R. T. (1995) Plant bugs of the world (Insecta: Heteroptera: Miridae): Systematic catalog, distributions, host list, and bibliography. New York Entomological Society, New York, xii + 1329 pp." type="book" year="1995">
Schuh, 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FDFFFC981488FC91" box="[605,664,836,861]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="1995.0">1995</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA7F19BBC7FD921FD07FC9815BDFC90" author="Wachmann" box="[677,941,836,861]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Wachmann, E., Melber, A. &amp; Deckert, J. (2004) Wanzen. 2. Cimicomorpha: Microphysidae (Flechtenwanzen), Miridae (Weichenwanzen). Neubearbeitung der Wanzen Deutschlands, Osterreichs und der deutschsprachigen Schweiz. Die Tierwelt Deutschlands, 75, 1 - 288. [Goecke &amp; Evers, Keltern]" type="journal article" year="2004">
Wachmann et al., 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FCD0FC9815BDFC90" box="[882,941,836,860]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA7F19BBC7FD921FC18FC981274FC90" author="Wheeler" box="[954,1124,836,861]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Wheeler, A. G. Jr. (2001) Biology of the Plant Bugs (Hemiptera: Miridae), Pests, Predators, Opportunists. Cornell University Press, Ithaca and London, xv + 507 pp." type="book" year="2001">
Wheeler, 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FB8AFC981274FC90" box="[1064,1124,836,860]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2001.0">2001</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry id="F321CCFABC7FD921FB3AFC9812EEFC91" box="[1176,1278,836,861]" name="Thailand" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Thailand</collectingCountry>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FAA9FC99138CFC90" box="[1291,1436,837,860]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="siamensis">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FAA9FC99138CFC90" box="[1291,1436,837,860]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">H. siamensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was discovered on inflorescence of 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FD8FFCB4149FFC4C" box="[557,655,872,896]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Loranthaceae" genus="Scurrula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Santalales" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FD8FFCB4149FFC4C" box="[557,655,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Scurrula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FD1DFCB414DDFC4C" box="[703,717,872,896]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="1.0">1</number>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FD7FFCBB1568FC4C" box="[733,888,871,896]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Loranthaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Santalales" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Loranthaceae</taxonomicName>
) growing on 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FBB2FCB4125EFCB3" box="[1040,1102,872,895]" class="Gastropoda" family="Ficidae" genus="Ficus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FBB2FCB4125EFCB3" box="[1040,1102,872,895]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Ficus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. (
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FB24FCB412E8FC4C" box="[1158,1272,872,896]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Moraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Moraceae</taxonomicName>
) in November (
<figureCitation id="130D90EFBC7FD921FF3DFC5016CFFC68" box="[159,223,908,933]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1742,1764]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,193,1720]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[152,1435,193,1721]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Hosts and habitats of Hypseloecus. A. Sarika near Nangrong Waterfall, Nakhon Nayok Province, Thailand. B. Sarika near Sarika Waterfall." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/290610/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
Fig. 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FF76FC5016CFFC68" box="[212,223,908,932]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
A). Many adults and immatures of three species, 
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FCACFC51123EFC68" box="[782,1070,908,932]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FCACFC5115B2FC68" box="[782,930,909,932]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="castaneus">H. castaneus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FC0CFC51123EFC68" box="[942,1070,908,932]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="katrinae">H. katrinae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FBC4FC51131DFC68" box="[1126,1293,909,932]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sericosagus">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FBC4FC51131DFC68" box="[1126,1293,909,932]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">H. sericosagus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, were found to co-occur on flowers and fruits of 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FD8BFC6C149BFC04" box="[553,651,944,968]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Loranthaceae" genus="Scurrula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Santalales" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FD8BFC6C149BFC04" box="[553,651,944,968]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Scurrula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FD1BFC6C14D7FC04" box="[697,711,944,968]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2.0">2</number>
heavily parasitizing 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FC12FC6C12D0FC0B" authority="Lour." authorityName="Lour." box="[944,1216,944,967]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Homonoia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="riparia">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FC12FC6C126CFC0B" box="[944,1148,944,967]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Homonoia riparia</emphasis>
Lour.
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FB6FFC731367FC04" box="[1229,1399,943,968]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Euphorbiaceae</taxonomicName>
) in March (
<figureCitation id="130D90EFBC7FD921FF52FC08173FFC20" box="[240,303,980,1005]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1742,1764]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,193,1720]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[152,1435,193,1721]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Hosts and habitats of Hypseloecus. A. Sarika near Nangrong Waterfall, Nakhon Nayok Province, Thailand. B. Sarika near Sarika Waterfall." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/290610/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
Fig. 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FE86FC08173FFC20" box="[292,303,980,1004]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
B). Flowers of 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FE7FFC08142FFC20" box="[477,575,980,1004]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Loranthaceae" genus="Scurrula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Santalales" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FE7FFC08142FFC20" box="[477,575,980,1004]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Scurrula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FDCFFC08146BFC20" box="[621,635,980,1004]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="1.0">1</number>
and sp. 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FD78FC0814F8FC20" box="[730,744,980,1004]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2.0">2</number>
are obviously different from each other although they are yet to be identified.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B898C6ABC7FD921FF65FBC01511FB6C" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1869]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
Adults of 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FE9EFBC017DAFBF8" box="[316,458,1052,1076]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FE9EFBC017DAFBF8" box="[316,458,1052,1076]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Hypseloecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are often attracted to light at night. Collection records suggest that most of the 
<collectingCountry id="F321CCFABC7FD921FACAFBC0138CFBF9" box="[1384,1436,1052,1077]" name="Thailand" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Thai</collectingCountry>
species described below have two or more generations per year. In tropical forests, the hemiparasitic loranthaceous shrubs grow generally very high (near forest canopy), and, therefore, it is usually difficult to collect these mirids in satisfactory numbers as well as to survey their ecology.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B898C6ABC7FD921FF65FB701768FA98" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1869]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
The majority of 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FE20FB70141FFB08" box="[386,527,1196,1220]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FE20FB70141FFB08" box="[386,527,1196,1220]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Hypseloecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species have hitherto been known from the Australian and Afrotropical regions (Schuh, 
<date id="FF88AAAABC7FD921FF54FB0C1769FB24" box="[246,377,1232,1256]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2002" valueMax="2014">
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FF54FB0C1769FB24" box="[246,377,1232,1256]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2008.0" valueMax="2014.0" valueMin="2002.0">2002–2014</number>
</date>
). Now the genus is revealed to be widely distributed in the Old World, including continental Asia. There are some more undescribed species in 
<collectingCountry id="F321CCFABC7FD921FD75FB281554FAC1" box="[727,836,1268,1293]" name="Indonesia" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F321CCFABC7FD921FCDEFB2815AFFAC1" box="[892,959,1268,1293]" name="Nepal" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Nepal</collectingCountry>
(Yasunaga, unpublished data), in addition to two known Asian species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FE7CFAC514FEFAFC" authority="Schuh, 1984" authorityName="Schuh" authorityYear="1984" box="[478,750,1303,1328]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ifugao">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FE7CFAC51459FAFC" box="[478,585,1304,1328]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">H. ifugao</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFA7F19BBC7FD921FDF5FACB14F5FAFC" author="Schuh" box="[599,741,1303,1328]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Schuh, R. T. (1984) Revision of the Phylinae (Hemiptera, Miridae) of the Indo-Pacific. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 177, 1 - 476." type="journal article" year="1984">
Schuh, 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FD0EFAC414F5FAFC" box="[684,741,1304,1328]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="1984.0">1984</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from the 
<collectingCountry id="F321CCFABC7FD921FCF9FACB15C9FAFC" box="[859,985,1303,1328]" name="Philippines" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Philippines</collectingCountry>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FBADFAC5134EFAFC" authority="Yasunaga, 2001" authorityName="Yasunaga" authorityYear="2001" box="[1039,1374,1304,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="takahashii">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FBADFAC512B7FAFC" box="[1039,1191,1304,1328]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">H. takahashii</emphasis>
Yasunaga, 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FA84FAC4134EFAFC" box="[1318,1374,1304,1328]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2001.0">2001</number>
</taxonomicName>
from the Ryukyus, 
<collectingCountry id="F321CCFABC7FD921FE92FAE11764FA98" box="[304,372,1341,1364]" name="Japan" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Japan</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32CDFE1BC7FD921FF65FABC1415F881" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8B898C6ABC7FD921FF65FABC16EDF99C" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1869]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FF65FABC1744FAB4" box="[199,340,1376,1400]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FF65FABC1744FAB4" box="[199,340,1376,1400]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Hypseloecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forms the second most species-rich genus in the tribe 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FC12FA831221FAB4" box="[944,1073,1375,1400]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Pilophorini">Pilophorini</taxonomicName>
, following a typical ant-mimetic genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FF42FA5817B1FA51" authority="Hahn" authorityName="Hahn" box="[224,417,1412,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Pilophorus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FF42FA58174CFA50" box="[224,348,1412,1436]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Pilophorus</emphasis>
Hahn
</taxonomicName>
which includes more than 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FD71FA5814EDFA50" box="[723,765,1412,1436]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="120.0">120</number>
described species. 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FC7AFA581246FA51" box="[984,1110,1412,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Pilophorini">Pilophorini</taxonomicName>
is assumed to consist of two basic lineages, one oligophagous, non ant-mimetic group and another more or less (sometimes strikingly) antlike and predaceous group (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA7F19BBC7FD921FE04FA1014C3FA28" author="Yasunaga" box="[422,723,1484,1509]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Yasunaga, T. &amp; Schuh, R. T. (2013) Morphologically novel members of the ant-mimetic plant bug genus Pilophorus Hahn found in Thailand, with descriptions of three new species (Heteroptera: Miridae: Phylinae: Pilophorini). American Museum Novitates, 3768, 1 - 18. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1206 / 3768.2" type="journal article" year="2013">
Yasunaga &amp; Schuh, 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FD35FA1014C3FA28" box="[663,723,1484,1508]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2013.0">2013</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA7F19BBC7FD921FD40FA1115F3FA28" author="Yasunaga" box="[738,995,1484,1509]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Yasunaga, T., Yamada, K. &amp; Artchawakom, T. (2014) Additional records and descriptions of the ant-mimetic plant bug genus Pilophorus from Thailand (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Miridae: Phylinae: Pilophorini). Zootaxa, 3795 (1), 1 - 15. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3795.1.1" type="journal article" year="2014">
Yasunaga 
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FCFBFA111585FA28" box="[857,917,1484,1508]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">et al.</emphasis>
, 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FC04FA1015F3FA28" box="[934,995,1484,1508]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2014.0">2014</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). All species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FB04FA101324FA28" box="[1190,1332,1484,1508]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FB04FA101324FA28" box="[1190,1332,1484,1508]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Hypseloecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are now known to be associated strictly with the santalalean host plants. Of the four phytophagous (genus) groups present in Asia (
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FF7CF9C817A8F9E0" authority="Reuter" authorityName="Reuter" box="[222,440,1556,1580]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Sthenaridea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FF7CF9C81774F9E0" box="[222,356,1556,1580]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Sthenaridea</emphasis>
Reuter
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FE6BF9C814C7F9E1" authority="Miller" authorityName="Miller" box="[457,727,1556,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Parasthenaridea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FE6BF9C81495F9E0" box="[457,645,1556,1580]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Parasthenaridea</emphasis>
Miller
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FCB7F9C81218F9E1" authority="Poppius" authorityName="Poppius" box="[789,1032,1556,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Lasiolabops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FCB7F9C8158EF9E0" box="[789,926,1556,1580]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Lasiolabops</emphasis>
Poppius
</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FBBCF9C812BBF9E0" box="[1054,1195,1556,1580]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FBBCF9C812BBF9E0" box="[1054,1195,1556,1580]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Hypseloecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears to the most speciose.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B898C6ABC7FD921FF65F9811415F881" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1869]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
Recent works based on both morphology and 
<collectionCode id="ED2714AFBC7FD921FD77F9801502F9B8" LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" box="[725,786,1628,1652]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" name="Department of Natural Resources, Environment, The Arts and Sport" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">DNA</collectionCode>
sequence data (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA7F19BBC7FD921FC6BF98012C9F9B8" author="Schuh" box="[969,1241,1628,1653]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Schuh, R. T. &amp; Menard, K. (2011) Santalalean-feeding plant bugs: ten new species in the genus Hypseloecus Reuter from Australia and South Africa (Heteroptera: Miridae: Phylinae): their hosts and placement in the Pilophorini. Australian Journal of Entomology, 50, 365 - 392. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1440 - 6055.2011.00829. x" type="journal article" year="2011">
Schuh &amp; Menard, 
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FB3DF98012C9F9B8" box="[1183,1241,1628,1652]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2011.0">2011</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA7F19BBC7FD921FB45F9801331F9B8" author="Menard" box="[1255,1313,1628,1652]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Schuh, R. T. &amp; Menard, K. (2013) A revised classification of the Phylinae (Insecta: Heteroptera: Miridae): Arguments for the placement of genera. American Museum Novitates, 3785, 1 - 72. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1206 / 3785.2" type="journal article" year="2013">
<number id="3DFE9E4DBC7FD921FB45F9801331F9B8" box="[1255,1313,1628,1652]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2013.0">2013</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) improved our knowledge about the phylogenetic position of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FCAAF9A3159AF954" box="[776,906,1663,1688]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Pilophorini">Pilophorini</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FBAFF95C128AF954" box="[1037,1178,1664,1688]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FBAFF95C128AF954" box="[1037,1178,1664,1688]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Hypseloecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is currently treated as paraphyletic in their analyses involving molecular data (unfortunately lacking any Asian species), although this genus is considered in all likelihood to be a monophyletic group, judging from the morphological characters and information on the biology. There are still quite a few undescribed species in the Oriental Region and subtropical Asia. To demonstrate the more satisfactory classification of 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F7E9BC7FD921FC9CF8CC15DBF8E4" box="[830,971,1808,1832]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9425078BC7FD921FC9CF8CC15DBF8E4" box="[830,971,1808,1832]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Hypseloecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, broader surveys of characters as well as of the Asian faunas are required.
</paragraph>
